		{
			dependencies: ["5F2D9F4908401D0D"]
			description: ["Peripherals are the main way your computers do things in the game world! You can access them using the \"&dperipheral&f\" library, and you can assign them to a variable with the \"&ewrap()&r\" function."]
			id: "0B55AC33D41FED67"
			subtitle: "Internet of Things"
			tasks: [{
				id: "6E4CFA68098E43CB"
				title: "Peripherals"
				type: "checkmark"
			}]
			x: 2.0d
			y: 3.5d
		}
		{
			dependencies: ["160EC57392A6C5D5"]
			description: [
				"You don't wrap &3bundled cables&r as peripherals, but you can use \"&egetBundledOutput()&r\" and \"&egetBundledInput()&r\" from the \"&dredstone&r\" library to send and recieve color-coded signals! "
				""
				"It's a little unintuitive though. Each &3bundled cable&r tracks the state of each color with a 16 bit integer, with each bit mappping onto the state of each color."
				""
				"The CC wiki (linked with the book icon earlier in the chapter) gives you a table that shows which bits go to which colors under the \"&dcolors&r\" library."
				""
				"If you know your bitwise operations, great! Otherwise, just add together the numbers in the \"dec\" column for all the colors you want ON."
				"So if you just want blue and cyan to be on, plug in 2560 (which is 2048 + 512)."
			]
			id: "0E61A782522AC382"
			subtitle: "Technially not a peripheral"
			tasks: [{
				id: "68C994632CF7AD03"
				item: "morered:bundled_network_cable"
				type: "item"
			}]
			x: 1.0d
			y: 0.0d
		}
		{
			dependencies: [
